<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF88C10DB9FB260CFE24F806" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF88C10DB9FB260CFE24F806" blockId="6.[151,1437,788,1966]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF88C10DB9FB260CFE83F822" bold="true" box="[199,334,1904,1930]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="70D07566FF88C10DBA74260CFC4FF822" box="[840,898,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">dent-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="70D07566FF88C10DBA89260CFBD8F822" box="[949,1045,1904,1930]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">sacculus</emphasis>
, referring to the basally denticulate sacculus in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
